  // Silently ignore - plugin failures must not crash OpenCode\\n     // console.debug('[Entire] Hook call failed:', e)\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n3. **[hooks.go:50-56] Idempotency check could use file hash**\\n\\n   The idempotency check reads the file and checks for the marker string. This works, but if the plugin content changes (due to version updates), reinstalling would require `--force`. Consider also checking if the content matches expected template.\\n\\n4. **[types.go:76-80] FileModificationTools should be exhaustive**\\n\\n   The `FileModificationTools` list includes `edit`, `write`, `patch`. If OpenCode adds new file modification tools, this list would need updating. Consider adding a comment noting this dependency:\\n\\n   ```go\\n   // FileModificationTools are tools in OpenCode that modify files on disk.\\n   // NOTE: Keep in sync with OpenCode's internal/llm/tools/*.go files.\\n   var FileModificationTools = []string{\\n   ```\\n\\n5. **[lifecycle.go:95] Consistent with other agents - good**\\n\\n   The `//nolint:nilnil` comment for unknown hooks is consistent with Claude Code and Gemini CLI implementations.\\n\\n### Praise\\n\\n1. **Excellent interface consistency** - The OpenCode agent correctly implements all required Agent interface methods and optional interfaces (`HookSupport`, `TranscriptAnalyzer`, `TokenCalculator`).\\n\\n2. **Well-structured code organization** - The code is cleanly separated into:\\n   - `opencode.go` - Identity and session management\\n   - `hooks.go` - Hook installation (similar pattern to other agents)\\n   - `lifecycle.go` - Event parsing (follows the established pattern)\\n   - `transcript.go` - Format-specific parsing\\n   - `types.go` - Type definitions\\n   - `cli_commands.go` - External CLI interactions\\n\\n3. **Good test coverage** - Unit tests cover:\\n   - Hook installation/uninstallation\\n   - All lifecycle event parsing\\n   - Transcript parsing with various edge cases\\n   - Token usage calculation\\n   - Chunk/r